   <mods:abstract>The purpose of this study is to highlight word painting and motivic material in Paul Hindemith's Das Marienleben. Throughout history, these devices have been compositional techniques used by many composers. This treatise will be helpful in interpreting Hindemith's Das Marienleben and approaching the music from an experimental view. The life of Mary is shrouded in mystery; the Bible says little about her before she is visited by Gabriel or after Jesus ascends to heaven. Rilke uses poetic license to fill out the unknown details of Mary's life and Hindemith interprets the poetry by creating a dynamic song cycle that starts with Mary's birth and concludes with her own ascension into heaven. This study includes figures with highlighted motives, discussion of significant moments within the music, and scriptural passages and poetry that introduce each song. Readers will also find a complete IPA (International Phonetic Alphabet) transcription, a glossary of terminology, and a translated edition of Hindemith's opening remarks on the cycle. The last scholarly writings about Das Marienleben were published over twenty years ago and this treatise aims to bring a new perspective in approaching his music.</mods:abstract>
